        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The letter is in an album of autograph letters compiled for <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_8002.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edith Emma Topham</ref> by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4314.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Sharpey</ref>; most of the letters in the album are addressed to Sharpey, but this letter is to Edith’s father, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6884.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Topham</ref>, from CD. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6884.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Topham</ref> was a medical student at University College, London, during the time that Sharpey was professor of anatomy and physiology there. Topham had written to CD after reading <hi rend="italic">Expression</hi>, remarking that when Shakespeare in <hi rend="italic">Romeo and Juliet</hi> suggested that Juliet did not blush in the dark, he meant that the blush was unseen, not that it was absent. Topham’s letter has been lost, but the sense of it was preserved in a note in <hi rend="italic">Expression</hi> 2d ed., p. 355 n. 38; see also <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 20, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8660G.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Mr Topham, 5 December 1872</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
